Note:
SYSCALL MANAGER — runtime-side wrapper

This file is the RUNTIME's interface to the OS syscall layer. The actual
syscall instruction is issued by compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa
(platform router) which delegates to per-platform implementations in
compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/<plat>/syscall.runa. Those primitive
files use Runa's `Inline Assembly:` feature to embed the syscall instruction
directly.

This file's job is THREE-FOLD:

  1. EXPORT C-runtime-compatible entry points so user code and compiler-
     generated code can call familiar names (system_call, exit_with_code).
     This lets us drop in runtime.o and replace runtime.c without any
     calling-code changes.

  2. PROVIDE error translation. Linux returns negative errno values from
     syscalls; this layer offers helpers to detect failure (errno_check)
     and translate to typed Runa errors (errno_to_error_code).

  3. PROVIDE convenience for retry-on-EINTR loops. Many syscalls are
     interruptible by signals; the canonical pattern is to retry on EINTR.
     This layer offers retry-wrapped variants for read/write/wait.

Architecture
------------

  runtime/integration/system_interface/syscall_manager.runa  (this file)
                            |
                            v
  compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa         (platform router)
                            |
                            v
  compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/<plat>/syscall.runa  (inline asm)
                            |
                            v
                       syscall instruction

What this file does NOT do
--------------------------
- Does NOT duplicate the syscall implementation. The platform-specific
  primitives are the single source of truth for issuing syscalls.
- Does NOT define syscall numbers, flags, or constants. Those live in the
  platform-specific files.
- Does NOT implement file/socket/process operations directly. Those are in:
    runtime/io/filesystem/file_operations.runa
    runtime/io/network/...
    runtime/integration/system_interface/wrappers/process_manager.runa
  This file provides the lowest-level dispatch and exit primitives only.

Dependencies
------------
- compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 — C-runtime-compatible entry points (the symbols runtime.o exports)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: system_call - generic syscall dispatcher.

Note: This is the C-runtime-compatible entry point. Stage1's compiler-generated
Note: code calls `system_call(num, a1, a2, a3, a4, a5, a6)` directly when it
Note: needs raw kernel access (rare; most code uses higher-level wrappers).
Note: Replaces the legacy `system_call` from v0.0.8.4.5.3.5/runtime/runtime.c
Note: which was a C variadic stub forwarding to the syscall instruction.

Note: The result is the kernel's return value: negative values indicate -errno,
Note: non-negative values are success (fd, byte count, pid, etc. depending on
Note: which syscall was invoked).
Process called "system_call" takes num as Integer, a1 as Integer, a2 as Integer, a3 as Integer, a4 as Integer, a5 as Integer, a6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Return syscall_6 from Syscall with num, a1, a2, a3, a4, a5, a6
End Process

Note: exit_with_code - terminate the process with the given exit code.

Note: Uses SYS_EXIT_GROUP which terminates every thread in the process. The
Note: per-thread SYS_EXIT alternative is wrong for libc-style exit() semantics;
Note: we always want the entire process to exit. The platform router resolves
Note: SYS_EXIT_GROUP to the correct syscall number for the current target
Note: (e.g. 231 on Linux x86-64, different on Darwin/BSD/Windows/etc.) — never
Note: hardcode the number here, the router is the single source of truth and
Note: this code stays valid across all 18+ supported platform/architecture
Note: combinations.

Note: This function does not return. The caller's stack is abandoned; finalizers
Note: registered via Runa's panic/recover machinery are NOT run here. For
Note: graceful shutdown that runs finalizers, use the higher-level
Note: services/error_handling/shutdown.runa entry point.
Process called "exit_with_code" takes code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let exit_group_num be proc SYS_EXIT_GROUP from Syscall
    Let dummy be syscall_1 from Syscall with exit_group_num, code
    Note: Defensive infinite loop in case the kernel returns (it should not).
    Note: Ensures we never return to the caller even on a kernel/platform
    Note: that doesn't honor exit_group for some reason.
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set dummy to syscall_1 from Syscall with exit_group_num, code
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: exit - alias for exit_with_code, matching libc's exit().
Process called "exit" takes code as Integer returns Integer:
    Return exit_with_code(code)
End Process

Note: _exit - alias for exit_with_code, matching libc's _exit() (no atexit handlers).
Note: Runa does not currently run atexit handlers from exit() either, so the
Note: distinction is purely historical / for source compatibility.
Process called "_exit" takes code as Integer returns Integer:
    Return exit_with_code(code)
End Process


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 — Errno detection and translation
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Linux syscall convention: negative return values in [-4095, -1] indicate
Note: errno = -result. Any value >= 0 is success. (4095 = MAX_ERRNO; values more
Note: negative than -4095 are valid pointers/handles, not errors.)


Note: errno_check - returns 1 if the result represents an error, 0 otherwise.
Note: Use after any syscall to determine success/failure before consuming result.
Process called "errno_check" takes result as Integer returns Integer:
    If result is less than 0:
        If result is greater than -4096:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: errno_value - extract the positive errno from a failed syscall result.
Note: Returns 0 if the result was not an error (caller should check first).
Process called "errno_value" takes result as Integer returns Integer:
    If errno_check(result) is equal to 1:
        Return -result
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Named errno constants. These are the standard Linux errno values from
Note: /usr/include/asm-generic/errno-base.h and errno.h. Provided as Process
Note: returning Integer to be consistent with the platform/<plat>/syscall.runa
Note: convention.

Process called "EPERM" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ENOENT" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "ESRCH" returns Integer:
    Return 3
End Process

Process called "EINTR" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "EIO" returns Integer:
    Return 5
End Process

Process called "ENXIO" returns Integer:
    Return 6
End Process

Process called "E2BIG" returns Integer:
    Return 7
End Process

Process called "ENOEXEC" returns Integer:
    Return 8
End Process

Process called "EBADF" returns Integer:
    Return 9
