Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 — EINTR retry helpers
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Slow syscalls (read, write, wait, accept, connect, poll, etc.) can be
Note: interrupted by signals, returning -EINTR. The canonical pattern is to
Note: retry. These wrappers do that automatically. Use them in preference to
Note: direct syscall calls when the syscall is interruptible and you don't
Note: have signal-driven cancellation logic.

Note: read_retry - read into buffer, retrying on EINTR.
Note: Returns the same values as raw read: bytes read (>=0), or -errno (other than -EINTR).
Process called "read_retry" takes fd as Integer, buf as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let result be syscall_read from Syscall with fd, buf, count
        If result is greater than or equal to 0:
            Return result
        End If
        If result is not equal to -4:
            Note: -EINTR = -4. Anything else, return the error.
            Return result
        End If
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: write_retry - write from buffer, retrying on EINTR.
Note: Note: a SHORT WRITE (result < count without an error) is not retried
Note: here; callers should loop on partial writes themselves. EINTR with zero
Note: bytes written IS retried because no progress was made.
Process called "write_retry" takes fd as Integer, buf as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let result be syscall_write from Syscall with fd, buf, count
        If result is greater than or equal to 0:
            Return result
        End If
        If result is not equal to -4:
            Return result
        End If
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: write_full - write exactly count bytes, looping until all are written
Note: or a non-EINTR error occurs. Returns count on success, or -errno on error.
Process called "write_full" takes fd as Integer, buf as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be 0
    While total is less than count:
        Let remaining be count minus total
        Let cur_buf be buf plus total
        Let result be write_retry(fd, cur_buf, remaining)
        If result is less than 0:
            Return result
        End If
        If result is equal to 0:
            Note: write() returning 0 on a regular fd is unusual but possible
            Note: on some kernels for zero-length writes. Treat as completion
            Note: to avoid infinite loop.
            Return total
        End If
        Set total to total plus result
    End While
    Return total
End Process

Note: read_full - read exactly count bytes, looping until all are read or EOF
Note: or a non-EINTR error. Returns count on full read, less-than-count if EOF
Note: reached before count bytes, or -errno on error.
Process called "read_full" takes fd as Integer, buf as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be 0
    While total is less than count:
        Let remaining be count minus total
        Let cur_buf be buf plus total
        Let result be read_retry(fd, cur_buf, remaining)
        If result is less than 0:
            Return result
        End If
        If result is equal to 0:
            Note: EOF reached before getting full count. Return partial.
            Return total
        End If
        Set total to total plus result
    End While
    Return total
End Process


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 — Helper / introspection
Note: ============================================================================

Note: syscall_is_supported - check whether the running kernel supports the given
Note: syscall number. Used by feature-detection paths in higher-level wrappers
Note: (e.g. preferring statx() over fstat() when available).

Note: Implementation: invoke the syscall with invalid arguments; if the kernel
Note: returns -ENOSYS (-38) the syscall is not implemented. Any other error (or
Note: success) indicates the syscall exists. This is the standard libc pattern.

Note: WARNING: this MAY have side effects depending on the syscall — only use
Note: for syscalls that are safe to call with invalid args (which is most of
Note: them, since invalid-arg detection happens before any state change).
Process called "syscall_is_supported" takes num as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be syscall_0 from Syscall with num
    Let errno be errno_value(result)
    If errno is equal to ENOSYS():
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: End of syscall_manager.runa
